    <section id="id847771">
      <title>Solid state </title>
      <para id="id1172523455575">In the solid state the compounds of the alkali metals generally form ionic lattices, e.g., Na<sup>+</sup>Cl<sup>-</sup>. These structures are essentially electrostatic in nature and the lattice energy is usually defined as the enthalpy of formation of the ionic compound from gaseous ions and as such is invariably exothermic. </para>
      
      
      <equation id="eip-413"><media id="id6742782_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics2-70d0.jpg" id="id6742782__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>


        </media></equation><para id="id1172523326220">In all cases the lattice energies is high and is found to be proportional to the ratio of the charges on the ions and the sum of the ionic radii (r). </para>
      
      <equation id="eip-158"><media id="id8363956_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics3-ed43.jpg" id="id8363956__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
          </media>
        </equation><para id="id1172523479789">The ionic radii for alkali metal cations are given in <link target-id="id7918480"/>; those for common anions are given in <link target-id="eip-69"/>. </para>
      <table id="eip-69" summary="Ionic radii of common anions.">
