      <para id="id6819863">As an example, the structure of KBr can be predicted from the data in <link target-id=" id7918480"/> and <link target-id="eip-69"/>. The ionic radius of K<sup>+</sup> is 1.33 Å, while that for Br<sup>-</sup> is 1.96 Å. The ratio of the ionic radii (r<sup>+</sup>/r<sup>-</sup>) is 0.67. Hence, KBr has a NaCl (rock salt) structure. </para>
      
      <exercise id="eip-788"><problem id="eip-539">
  <para id="eip-480">
 What is the structure of NaH?
  </para>
</problem>

<solution id="eip-429">
  <para id="eip-813">
    The ionic radius of Na<sup>+</sup> is 0.97 Å, while that for H<sup>-</sup> is 1.54 Å. The ratio of the ionic radii (r<sup>+</sup>/r<sup>-</sup>) is 0.67. Hence, NaH has a NaCl (rock salt) structure.
  </para>
</solution>
</exercise><exercise id="eip-915"><problem id="eip-649">
  <para id="eip-213">
    What is the structure of RbF?
  </para>
</problem>

<solution id="eip-546">
  <para id="eip-911">
   The ionic radius of Rb<sup>+</sup> is 1.47 Å, while that for F<sup>-</sup> is 1.33 Å. The ratio of the ionic radii (r<sup>+</sup>/r<sup>-</sup>) is 1.10. Hence, RbF has a CsCl structure.
  </para>
</solution>
</exercise>
      
      
